The first virtual provider is already coming to Czech Republic this year.
Maybe
The mobile telecommunications market in the Czech Republic is quite mature, the Czech providers offer virtually all services, as they are offered by their partners in Western Europe.
Nevertheless, something is missing here - a virtual provider that forces the classic at lower prices.
Maybe he won't wait for a long time.
That the Czech mobile telephone providers are working for the most expensive in Europe at all, we have often reported on Mobil.cz.
This also confirmed the Telecommunications Authority ČTÚ, who pointed out that the price for a SMS is higher here than in the rest of the European Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the field of roaming fees regulation, there is as likely a paradoxal situation - for some customers of the Czech mobile telephone providers, SMS will be cheaper from abroad than at home.
Why are the prices in Czech Republic so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, it is lacking the competition that really makes a fight.
Perhaps it sounds paradox, but in Czech Republic there are three mobile networks and a penetration of far more than 100%.
On the other hand, mobile telephone providers would like to shrink that there is extremely much competition on the Czech market.
The President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (ČTÚ) Pavel Dvořák, who often said in the past that there is no room for another supplier in Czech Republic.
It is probably true that a classic provider with a own network no longer has a lot of opportunities (or, it would probably not find any frequencies).
But there is another option - a virtual provider.
Just the entry of virtual providers to the mobile market brought a significant price reduction, which then had to respond to the classic mobile providers.
Before the entry of companies such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile on the market in Britain, there were voices similar to those in Czech Republic.
However, it has been shown that there is space for such providers and that they can really be successful.
On the other hand, you don't need to look for examples long.
In February this we reported about the start of the virtual provider Mobilking in Poland.
In only half a year, this provider managed to win more than 100 thousand customers, thus rising to the fifth largest supplier of the country.
At the back of Mobilking, the Penta Financial Group is held in Czech Republic, among other things U:fon.
The advantage of virtual providers is to focus on a much more specific target group.
In order to function effectively, virtual providers need much less customers than a classic provider.
They do not need relatively high costs for the construction, operation and entertainment of a mobile network.
In the world, virtual providers are usually profiled as low-cost companies - they offer cheap telephone calls and SMS, which is often accompanied by a less comprehensive service offer.
For example, Tesco Mobile in Great Britain offers at least half cheaper SMS than his competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be a rather good move to put on a non-clean target group.
This provider is specifically addressed to men.
"Choose real guys Mobilking - the provider who likes them and whom they can trust," says David Seibert, CEO of the Mobile Entertainment Company, the operator company of this virtual provider.
It is difficult to say whether a similar concept as in Poland could take foot in the Czech Republic.
The press speaker of Vodafone Miroslav Čepický also doubts: "The Czech market is relatively small for a market segment on which most virtual providers are based.
In addition, it is relatively saturated from the view of the service offer."
In Czech Republic without chance, the mobile phone providers mean
However, it is almost sure that when a virtual mobile provider acquires Czech Republic, this will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about an expansion of this successful project, but the negotiations in the Czech Republic do not look very hopeful.
It will rather come to a market entrance from Mobilking to other countries of our region," says in a telephone conversation for Mobil.cz Jana Studničková, press speaker of the Penta Financial Group.
Indirectly, it confirmed that the current mobile telephone providers in the Czech Republic are not specially associated with this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do everything for no potential competitor.
Your interest in launching a virtual mobile provider has been showing the GTS Novera Group, who wants to take a further step to become a real competitor of Telefónica O2 in the field of business customers.
"We have a great interest in offering our customers not only fixed networks but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the earlier, the better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this option with all Czech mobile providers.
With some of them we have already been able to achieve negotiations progress," said the press speaker of the Pavel Kaidl group.
Maybe better times are coming now.
Non-official information shows that the first virtual provider may be expected until the end of the year.
So far, however, this is surrounded by an inevitable wall of silence.
"On this moment, we do not assume that there is room for a full virtual provider in Czech Republic.
The Czech market has a great deal of specificity to other markets.
Until now, no subject has addressed us with a complex and serious project in this area," says in his explanation for Mobil.cz Vlastimil Sršeě from the press department of Telefónica O2.
The specificity of the Czech market also points to other suppliers.
The press speaker of T-Mobile Martina Kemrová, in rare conforming to the O2 explanation, adds: "We have not yet found a viable and both-sided advantageous project that could be built on."
And she adds: "In the T-Mobile network, no virtual provider will appear until the end of the year.
At this moment we must have a specific offer to think so short-term."
Vodafone focuses rather on the fulfilment of the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický says: "For negotiations with potential virtual providers, we are open, especially in the field of breakdown of costs and infrastructure.
This is just what we consider best from the viewpoint of the customers.
The main strategy of Vodafone in this area is searching for a partner to build a shared network for a fast mobile Internet."
The responsible authorities - hand-handed with the providers
The approach of mobile telephone providers is easy to understand, another provider has more competition, which would result in lower prices and thus also a decrease in profits.
So why should such a competitor facilitate the entry into the market?
That the providers can draw on a strike when it comes to something, it is also the long way forward and here about the origin of U:fon.
The strongest pressure in the direction of ČTÚ came from the company T-Mobile at the time when U:fone came to the market.
This also demonstrates publicly accessible information from the ČTÚ websites.
But now U:fon is suitable as an argument why a virtual provider should not be allowed.
Martina Kemrová noted: "The competitive environment of the mobile market has recently been strengthened by the entry into the market of a fourth mobile provider.
Taking into account the character of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that a new stakeholder would make high demands on the market itself and, in particular, its services."
However, in view of this approach by mobile telecommunications providers, the absolute disagreement of the Czech regulatory authorities is amazed.
This is not just the attitude of the ČTÚ, who, unfortunately, in Czech countries, unlike the United Kingdom and other highly developed countries, does not have the competence to intervene in economic competition.
It only holds the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (UOHS).
This, however, refers to this whole problem, its very typical attitude.
"The entry into the market of a virtual mobile telephone provider would then be possible after a contract concluded between a mobile provider and a virtual provider on the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
No such contract has been concluded so far, because the offer of potential interested parties was probably not enough interesting for the classic providers", so in his answer to our request Kristián Chalupa from the ÚOHS Department of External Relations.
The representatives of the suppliers would not surprise such a formulation.
This is more than questionable by an authority representing consumer interests and, inter alia, ensuring that nobody misuses its position on the market.
In particular, if Kristián Chalupa adds: "In abroad, where virtual providers work quite normally, it is observed that their market entry has contributed to a price reduction in mobile telephone services."
However, the pressure on the proper functioning of the market and a price reduction are probably not part of the interests of the UOHS.
