Hema-Quebec celebrated yesterday the 10th anniversary of her foundation, and her president, Dr. Francine Décary, had all reason to rejoice because Hema-Quebec has become one of the safest and most efficient blood banks in the world.
And above all, it has recovered public confidence, which had been severely shocked by the scandal of contaminated blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
As you know, the national blood reserves managed by the blood donation of the Canadian Red Cross during the 1980s were infected with the HI virus and the hepatitis C virus.
In view of this drama and the dissatisfaction of the public, the government of Canada launched a public investigation conducted by Judge Horace Krever in February 1994 aimed at bringing light into the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and drawing up directives in order to prevent a new disaster of this kind.
