The situation was discouraging.
Through the huge efforts to improve the safety of blood conserves and work in this area during the following years, we have recovered public confidence," she says, before she prides that early 2008, almost 94% of Quebec's population had confidence in Hema-Quebec.
Dr. Décary, however, keeps aware that "trust is something very violent".
Hema-Quebec has been acting in accordance with the principle of caution since its establishment on 28 September 1998.
At this time, we experienced the appearance of many cases of the human form of bovine madness in Europe, a new type of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, this woman who has been headed since the foundation of 1998.
`And we didn't have the least idea whether this disease could be transmitted through blood.
So we refer to one of the main directives of the reports of Krever and Gélineau, which is said to apply exclusive measures, if you do not know this and if a disease progresss only slowly, as it is evident in the case of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is expressed by a degeneration of the brain, which inevitably leads to death.
So, in April 1999, no blood was accepted by people who had stayed in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
Well, a few years ago, without any doubt, it was proved that this disease is transmitted via blood.
Thus this event has shown us that the principle of caution we applied has a sense.
In 1999, a much more precise technique appeared on the market for the detection of HIV: Nucleic acid tests (NSTs), which allow direct in the blood of the donor to prove the occurrence of the virus itself, and not the antibodies against the virus, as was the case in the tests used so far.
The NSTs made it possible to shorten the incubation time between the time when the person was infected and when the first viruses can be demonstrated by our techniques in the blood, the specialist explains.
This time could be reduced to a duration of less than one week.
Thus, the risk that some donors could be infected without knowing it and you could not recognize this has been significantly reduced.
These improvements made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of transmitting AIDS via a blood transfusion.
Today, one of 12 million people is at risk of receiving HIV-infected blood.
`In other words, it means that you would have to distribute 12 million blood conserves before someone was infected with HIV.
Since Hema-Quebec distributes between 40,000 and 500.000 blood conserves each year, it would take more than 24 years before a case occurs where HIV was transmitted via a blood conservation.
I believe that you can feel well today when you get or write a blood transfusion to restore health," says the director of Hema-Quebec.
`Our challenge for the next ten years is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know what pathogens can get into the system.
Only last year, the Chikungunya virus has appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the Westnil virus, is transmitted by insects through the blood.
We need to monitor without interruption," continues Dr. Décary before she emphasizes that Hema-Quebec must also provide sufficient supply in addition to a safe supply.
`The need rises because the population ages.
Since cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need new red blood cells or blood platelets.
The ageing of the population also affects the blood supply network, which is an average of only 3% of the appropriate inhabitants of Quebec. '
Every healthy person who is 18 years or older and fulfils the appropriate criteria can spend blood every 56 days, i.e. six times a year.
On average, 14% of the people who provide their blood are not assumed because they are, for example, sick of AIDS or malaria, and who are traveling to a country where malaria is spread, is excluded from the blood supply for a year.
`With these 3% we can get an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Missing stocks are very rare.
But you have to renew the members of this donor network when they get older and they can no longer spend blood.
It is difficult to convince people to spend blood, but especially to keep them and bring them to become regular donors.
