The psychology of survival - or why we are ready to pay more
In the case of auctions, buyers tend to spend more and therefore overestimate the error.
Neurologens and economic researchers at the University of New York have now succeeded in discovering the neurological-economic bases of this known and apparently irrational behavior.
According to a study published in the "Science" magazine, people do not want to be struck in a competition, such as an auction to eBay, and are therefore ready to pay even excessive prices.
The researchers have tried to explore the neurological schema of this "game" with experimental auctions.
A group of volunteers should play lotto, while the others participated in a playback action - in both cases the active brain regions of the subjects were examined by functional magnetic resonance (fMRI).
In both games the participants were able to win money, but an increased activity of the striatum, a complex below the brain, was measured in losers of the auction, where the survival of the opponent plays a key role.
In addition to many other functions, this brain region is responsible for the "self-rewarding" of the nervous system.
The researchers therefore believed that the increase in prices could be explained by avoiding an overreaction of Striatum.
In order to support these, the economists in the research group have carried out additional investigations to follow up the money.
In this case, three groups against one partner should be involved under different conditions.
The control group has been informed of the true value of the product and then they have done their efforts.
Another group was also promised 15 dollar rewards, in case they are a winner from the game.
The third group received 15 dollars before the auction, which were also lost in the event of a lost game.
The difference between both groups was therefore merely that the emphasis on one on the profit, while the other was on losing.
However, as a proof of the hypotheses expressed by neurologians, the members of the group of "to lose" were ready to make more efforts than those in the control or win group.
"These results can not be derived from any previous economic theory.
Indeed, these have justified the behaviour observed in auctions with the joy of gain or risk avoidance.
The contradiction between these two theories was resolved through the formative neurological procedures, so we now have a third explanation," said Andrew Schotter, professor of the New York University Economic Faculty.
