Intelligent car imitates the flight of the Hummel
What would be the best method for developing new technologies for accident prevention if not to imitate the natural barrier sensors?
For example, the bees.
The CEATEC in Japan presented an amazing project in which the Nissan engineers of Hummeln were inspired when creating new accidents avoiding systems.
In collaboration with the Tokiot University, Nissan has built the biomimetic system of type BR23C, a mini-car, equipped with the characteristics of bees, with the aim of supporting the development of a system that avoids any collision.
In the flight, each bee forms its own oval "Private Area", which is very similar to our own "protective sign", said Kazuhhiro Doi, product manager for technology-PR and research development, at the exhibition.
The composed eye of the bee, which can see in every direction and in an angle of over 300 degrees, play an important role.
In order to imitate the function of the composite eye, the researchers took the idea of the laser-controlled distance meter.
This identifies obstacles to the BR23C in a face field of 180 degrees within 2 meters, calculates their distances and sends signals to the microprocessor to board, which immediately introduces the collision avoiding process.
The obstacle is recorded in second break parts, and the authoroboter immediately changes the course, similar to the movement of bees, by turning the tyres around the corresponding angle.
Unlike existing systems, this manoeuvre takes place instinctively.
"If it wouldn't, the authoroboter could not respond quickly enough to avoid the obstacles," explained Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the "Mobility Laboratory" and the authoroboter project.
The system must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology corresponds to the innerest and most vulnerable part of the protective sign - a layer that is currently considered unavoidable within the accident.
The whole process must reflect the behaviour of bees when they eliminate other bees.
And that must be done in the fraction of a second.
However, in contrast to the bees, it can not go up, down, or even diagonal - it can only be two-dimensional, only towards the turnability of the tyres.
While the bees are infinitely open in order to eliminate other bees, the scientists could only use the rotational movement, or acceleration and braking.
The BR23C contains lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and more energy-efficient and therefore have longer life than traditional lithium ion batteries.
Andoh explained that it comes to the instinctive, intelligent reaction, and less to the processing of the data, and even less to the ability to store it.
This device only needs to process some inputs per second and respond accordingly to them.
It doesn't need to save it, or produce an intuitive, logical reaction using previous manoeuvre, so that it is currently using a handful of KB memory.
No Gigabyte and Megabyte hard memories are required.
This is the first step in the development of immediate collision prevention technology, which, according to Nissan's estimate, will be seriesly in production within the next ten years.
Another application could find the technology in the GPS satellite navigation by consciously directing the driver around obstacles and thus leading it to the target.
